{{Italic title}}
The '''Sesquicentennial March''' ({{lang-es|Marcha Sesquicentenario}}) is a well-known [[Peruvian music|Peruvian]] march, composed by the [[Peruvian people|Peruvian]] [[composer (music)|composer]] [[Jaime Díaz Orihuela]] ([[Arequipa]], 1927). The march, winner of a national contest for military music in celebration of the [[sesquicentennial]] of national independence in 1971, represents a grand combination of Andean sentiment and a pronounced martial theme. It is one of the more popular marches among those performed in parades and ceremonies in [[Peru]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filarmonia.org/page/Jaime-Diaz-Orihuela.aspx|title=Jaime Díaz Orihuela|accessdate=2 March 2014|website=Filarmonía 102.7 FM}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nayoulloa.com/numachu.html|title=Jaime Díaz Orihuela|website=Nayo Ulloa, Master of the Peruvian Flute (Kena)|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>

